Hmm I'm not too sure
=20
but the correlation coefficient must not be taken for its empirical counter=
part
=20
and the law of large numbers "tells" you roughly you can approximate a mean=
 by its empirical counterpart when the variables are identically distribute=
d and independant.
=20
If they are not independant, the empirical counterpart could be a not very =
good approximation.
=20
Then I have learned it's always better to use the Spearman's rho or the oth=
er one based on ranks, but not Pearson's correlation coefficient which is o=
nly the best in the normal setting. There is a book from Lehmann about this=
 ("Nonparametrics")
=20
